else:
    print("No pair found that adds up to the target.")
```

In this program, we iterate over the input list. For each number, we calculate its complement (i.e., target - current number). We then check if this complement exists in our dictionary. If it does, that means we have found a pair that adds up to the target, and we return these two numbers. If it doesn't exist, we add the current number and its index to the dictionary and continue.

If we finish iterating over the list without finding a pair that adds up to the target, we return None.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of elements in the input list. This is because each element is processed only once. The space complexity is also O(n) in the worst case scenario, where all elements are unique and hence, each element is stored in the dictionary.

